For the hydrothermal synthesis of CQD, Bixa orellana seeds were chosen as the carbon source without additional chemicals. The resultant pale brown solution indicates the successful carbonization of the Bixa orellana seeds. Under 360 nm UV light, the CQD solution showed a blue fluorescence. The QY of the CQD was obtained as 10.88 % (Fig. 2
                     ) as given in Table 1
                     .

Antioxidant activity measures a material's ability to neutralize free radicals. Several studies have reported on the antioxidant activity of CQDs [71–74]. The DPPH assay, a common method, uses a purple DPPH solution that turns yellow when interacting with antioxidants. CQD samples were added to a 1 mM ethanolic DPPH solution, and a decrease in absorbance at 517 nm was observed within 30 min. Results in Fig. 17
                        (a) showed that CQD's radical scavenging activity increased with concentration, from 48 % at 50 µg/mL to 93 % at 200 µg/mL. From the plot in Fig. 17(b), the EC50 value of CQD was obtained 48.09 µg/mL. The prominent radical inhibition activity is due to electron-donating groups on the CQD surface (–OH, –COOH) [75]. The DPPH solution changed from purple to yellow as CQD concentration increased (Fig. 18
                        ).
